    "title": "Game Rules",
    "classicTitle": "Classic mode (traditional Y)",
    "tetraTitle": "3D tetrahedron variant",
    "description1": "Y is a board game for two players in which participants take turns placing pieces of their color on a triangular board made up of hexagonal spaces.",
    "description2": "The objective of the game is to connect the three sides of the board with a continuous chain of pieces, and the first player to achieve this wins the game.",
    "description3": "The basic rules are very simple: each player places a piece of their color on an empty space during their turn, without moving or removing already placed pieces.",
    "description4": "The corners of the board count as belonging to the two adjacent sides, for example, a piece at the tip of the triangle belongs to both its left and right sides.",
    "classicRule1": "On each turn, place exactly one piece on an empty cell.",
    "classicRule2": "Already placed pieces cannot be moved or removed.",
    "classicRule3": "You win by connecting the three sides of the triangle with your chain.",
    "tetraIntro": "In 3D, the game is played on a tetrahedron surface: the objective changes from connecting sides to connecting faces.",
    "tetraRule1": "Each player tries to connect all 4 faces (A, B, C and D) with a continuous chain.",
    "tetraRule2": "Vertices and edges count for every touching face, so they are strategic positions.",
    "tetraRule3": "You can rotate the tetrahedron to inspect connections and blocks more clearly.",
    "tetraRule4": "You win when your network simultaneously connects all four tetrahedron faces.",
    "wikipedia": "Information taken from ",
    "wikipediaLink": "Wikipedia"
